We are proud to announce that Brian Shay (Canyon Crest Academy) has been elevated from finalist to recipient of the Presidential Award for Excellence in Mathematics and Science Teaching (PAEMST)!

The PAEMST program, administered by the National Science Foundation (NSF) on behalf of the White House Office of Science and Technology Policy, recognizes outstanding teachers for their contributions to the teaching and learning of science, technology, engineering, mathematics, and/or computer science.

"Mr. Brian Shay is one of the most accomplished math educators I have known, and I’m proud to call him a teacher on our campus," Canyon Crest Academy Principal Brett Killeen said. "Our students benefit from his teaching, and his colleagues benefit from his professional development expertise. He is incredibly deserving of this recognition!"

Brian's profile on the PAEMST website can be found at https://www.paemst.org/finalist_profile/5127

post_text:
We appreciate everyone’s passion and concern for how we will offer instruction in our district beginning on August 25, 2020. At this time, pursuant to Governor Newsom’s and the California Department of Public Health’s Guidelines, we do not have local control to open our schools for on-campus instruction until we are off of the State of California COVID-19 County Monitoring List for fourteen consecutive days.

The guidelines for our Distance Learning Model in the attachment to this post outline the significant differences from our spring 2020 program.

A full district update on the work that our staff has diligently planned for a number of scenarios ranging from reopening for on-campus instruction to full-time distance learning is available at www.sduhsd.net.

For the past five years, the conservatory students of the Canyon Crest Academy Envision Program have been working on Spirit Skies, a graphic novel series that teaches students about environmental stewardship. On Wednesday, July 22, a group of 12 CCA students under the direction of Timothy Stiven will present a panel, "Spirit Skies: How to publish an International youth comic in the Age of Covid-19", as a part of #ComicConAtHome hosted by Comicon International.

The world premiere of the panel will be shown for free at 6pm PT (July 22) at https://www.comic-con.org/cciathome/2020/video/PIh22lpvYJc.

You may be eligible to receive up to $365 per child to help feed your family. Because schools are closed due to COVID-19, families who are eligible for free or reduced-price meals can get extra food benefits to help feed their children. These benefits are called Pandemic EBT or P-EBT.

For more information, visit ca.p-ebt.org/info or call California’s EBT Customer Service Center (24 hours a day, seven days a week, at (877) 328-9677 for questions.

SACRAMENTO – Governor Gavin Newsom will provide an update tomorrow on the state’s response to the COVID-19 outbreak.

The update will be streamed at the @CAgovernor Twitter page and California Governor Facebook page.

WHEN: Wednesday, April 1, 2020 at 12:00 p.m. PDT

LIVESTREAM: @CAgovernor Twitter page and California Governor Facebook page.

San Diego Health and Human Services Agency issued a new Public Health Order effective March 29, 2020 at 12:00 AM. This new order continues school closures for an indefinite period of time. Although it is our hope that we will be able to reopen our schools before the end of the school year, we will comply with the order and keep our schools closed until further notice. We will continue to develop and extend our online learning program so that our students can be engaged, inspired and prepared.

post_text:
Congratulations to Brian Shay for being recognized by the San Diego County Board of Trustees as a finalist for the Presidential Award for Math and Science educators. @CCARaven @SanDiegoCOE

Brian Shay, a teacher at Canyon Crest Academy (San Dieguito Union High School District), is a finalist for the 2019 Presidential Awards for Excellence in Mathematics and Science Teaching.

Shay was selected as a finalist based on subject mastery, appropriate use of instructional methods and strategies, lifelong learning, and leadership in education beyond the classroom. The National Science Foundation and The White House choose the top honors in each state.

Shay is one of three mathematics finalists in the state. He has been teaching for 17 years and is the department chair at Canyon Crest Academy. He has won numerous awards, including the Distinguished Mathematics Teaching from the Mathematical Association of America.

post_text:
Carmel Valley Middle School celebrated its 20th Anniversary with a family event that included many students, staff, parents, and community members - past and present - who have made CVMS the remarkable place it is. Teachers Lorin Meyers, Shannon Merideth, and Katrina Peterson were joined by many Bobcats along with Board Trustee Joyce Dalessandro, who was a board member at the time they voted to open Carmel Valley Middle School, Board President Beth Hergesheimer, Trustee Melisse Mossy, Superintendent Dr. Robert Haley, and Deputy Superintendent Mark Miller for the cake cutting ceremony.
There were lots of games, awesome food trucks, music, dancing, plus 20 years of yearbooks to help alumni walk down memory lane. Go Bobcats!

post_text: SDUHSD Community - Last week, our Information Technology Department discovered an attempt to damage our network through a malware attack. They immediately took steps to protect our network and our information. We took many of our systems offline and we are carefully restoring access. We anticipate the Aeries Parent Portal will be back online by Wednesday morning.
text: SDUHSD Community - Last week, our Information Technology Department discovered an attempt to damage our network through a malware attack. They immediately took steps to protect our network and our information. We took many of our systems offline and we are carefully restoring access. We anticipate the Aeries Parent Portal will be back online by Wednesday morning.

post_text: SDUHSD Community - We are performing critical network security work this weekend in our operations center. To do this work we needed to take Aeries offline, however, we anticipate bringing it back online soon. We will post a message when we do. Thank you for your patience.

post_text: The 24th International Japanese Speech Contest for high school students was held in Matsuyama, Japan on July 25th. Zane Adlam, a Canyon Crest Academy Senior Raven, competed as one of 16 representatives from around the word. He did an outstanding as received the Best Audience Award. The convention center in Matsuyama was packed with 2000 audience members including his family, and his speech "My Promise with Grandma" moved everyone's heart. Zane completed Japanese 1, 2, and 3 and CCA and Advanced Placement Japanese at Torrey Pines High School. We are a team! Congratulations Zane!

post_text:
The Annual 16th All-USA High School Japanese Speech Contest was held at UC Irvine on Saturday, May 25th. 14 finalists from all over the country competed, and Zane Adlam (Canyon Crest Academy) who is currently taking AP Japanese course at TPHS won 1st place and became the U.S. national champion!! Congratulations to Zane on this outstanding achievement.

The winner of this contest will represent the USA and compete at the World Contest which will be held on July 25th in Japan. Since Zane is also accepted to attend the summer program at Columbia University during the same period, he will consult with his counselor for advice to make a decision for the next level.
text:
The Annual 16th All-USA High School Japanese Speech Contest was held at UC Irvine on Saturday, May 25th. 14 finalists from all over the country competed, and Zane Adlam (Canyon Crest Academy) who is currently taking AP Japanese course at TPHS won 1st place and became the U.S. national champion!! Congratulations to Zane on this outstanding achievement.

The winner of this contest will represent the USA and compete at the World Contest which will be held on July 25th in Japan. Since Zane is also accepted to attend the summer program at Columbia University during the same period, he will consult with his counselor for advice to make a decision for the next level.

post_text:
Team Paradox had a super fun trip to the Utah Regional competition in Salt Lake City. This has been the first time we have qualified for the Semifinals at our second regional in four years. We also won the Quality Award from Motorola which recognizes both a machine and a team that demonstrates ‘robustness.' We had about 30 students, 2 teachers, several mentors/parents, and one epic snowball fight! We are off to the world championships in Houston in a few weeks.
Here is an awesome four-minute highlights video of the UT competition. It does a great job describing what the whole program is about and our president Sarah Parkes spoke in many sections of it

Oak Crest Middle School
March 27, 2019 at 2:17 PM ·

In an effort to showcase our incredible school, two Oak Crest Middle School alumni jumped at the opportunity to return to their alma mater to assist with capturing the OCMS magic on video. Below is their creation, providing a brief glimpse into the daily life of a WAVE.

A special thank you to Alex Monko and Jack Bianchi for their support and creativity!

This video only touches the surface of the amazing elective opportunities we offer to students, so please make sure to visit the 2019-2020 Registration page on the OCMS website for videos on all of our dynamic elective offerings. This is especially important for our incoming students and families as they prepare for next year!

Enjoy!

The San Dieguito Union High School District online High School Selection window will open on Thursday, February 14, 2019, at 8:00 AM.

All current 8th-grade students who will be attending 9th grade in our District and all high school students who wish to change high schools need to select the high school that they wish to attend in fall 2019, before the close of the selection window at 4:00 PM on Friday, March 1, 2019.

No applications will be accepted after the March 1, 2019, 4:00 PM deadline. There will be no exceptions or special circumstances.

High school students who wish to remain at their current school do not need to make a selection; they will automatically be re-enrolled in their current high school for next year.

For more information: https://www.sduhsd.net/Parents--Students/High-School-Selection/index.html
